Millions in financial losses, imminent unemployment of trained private security officers and a possible closure of some companies. These are the grim prospects facing South Africa’s private security industry – a ripple effect arising from government printing works’ halting of operations due to the lockdown in response to the coronavirus. According to The Association of Private Security Owners of South Africa (Tapsosa) president Jones Maphalaphathwa, the closure of the government printer has affected the printing of firearm licences – adversely impacting on private security companies and over two million licensed firearm holders, whose renewed licences could not be printed. This,...